g.title: Folded Corner.104
g.desc: Interfaces provide a way to test our module in isolation by m...

g.text: Interfaces provide a way to test our module in isolation by means of mocks. Mocking provides a way to minimize our problem window to just the module-under-test, while we have absolute control over the dependencies it has. The result is: easier edge/use case testing, less time spent during test execution & creation and resolving issues faster.

g.title: Folded Corner.19
g.desc: To accomplish DIP we ensure that the ‘using’ client (=high le...

g.text: To accomplish DIP we ensure that the ‘using’ client (=high level module) is dependent up-on an abstraction. This means that the implementation behind that abstraction (= low level module) can be swapped/changed easily with a different concrete implementation. This results in lower time commitment and reduces bugs, because there is no need to adapt the ‘using’ client(s).

g.title: Rectangle.129
g.desc: Abstractions improve reusability of a module
g.text: Abstractions improve reusability of a module

g.title: Folded Corner.29
g.desc: Modules that are dependent on abstractions are flexible to be...

g.text: Modules that are dependent on abstractions are flexible to be reused with different concrete implementations. In contrast, modules dependent on the concrete implementation will be harder to re-use, because they are tightly coupled to the concrete type.

g.title: Folded Corner.102
g.desc: Applying DIP means applying abstractions. Abstractions create...

g.text: Applying DIP means applying abstractions. Abstractions create indirections and indirections create complexity. Indirections make it harder to navigate and debug code. On top of that, DIP heavily leans on dependency injection. This means the interface of our module increases in complexity in case its dependencies are injected. Applying DIP should be chosen carefully. A general rule is to apply it when likely change or reusability of a module is required. The only down-side of this approach is that testing frameworks enforce us to use abstractions to be able to mock the implementation accordingly. However, there are other options to test without having to use DIP. Test example: we have to test a module that has a private dependency or injects a concrete type. We first unit test the dependency thoroughly, so we are sure that it works accordingly. After that we test the module with integration tests.

g.title: Folded Corner.66
g.desc: Creating abstractions for each module, to adhere to DIP, will...

g.text: Creating abstractions for each module, to adhere to DIP, will increase the indirections in a software system. Indirections make software complex. Complexity results in more time spent, degrades design and introduces bugs.

g.title: Folded Corner.125
g.desc: An abstraction is a ‘contract’ that cannot be instantiated by...

g.text: An abstraction is a ‘contract’ that cannot be instantiated by other modules. An abstraction can be the language definition of an interface or an abstract class. Abstraction is one of the necessities to accomplish DIP.

g.title: Folded Corner.67
g.desc: Dependency injection (=DI) together with inheritance are the ...

g.text: Dependency injection (=DI) together with inheritance are the ‘wiring’ of the DIP principle. DI & inheritance ensure that we have the abstractions ‘bounded’ to our high and low-level modules.

g.title: Folded Corner.28
g.desc: When adhering to DIP the high-level modules are dependent on ...

g.text: When adhering to DIP the high-level modules are dependent on abstractions. This results in no re-compilation of the high-level modules incase the implementation behind the abstraction changes. This ensures less time during recompilation.

g.title: Folded Corner.37
g.desc: The test cases of a ‘using client’ that is dependent on the c...

g.text: The test cases of a ‘using client’ that is dependent on the concrete implementation of its dependency need modification and re-testing when a dependency ‘swap’ is introduced. In contrast, when adhering to DIP, the test suite of the ‘using client’ is not affected in case the concrete implementation ‘swaps’ and the interface remains the same.
